Political parties have been urged to provide support and funds to guarantee the maximum participation of women and youths during elections. This was part of the recommendations reached at a one day Webinar organised by Political Science Department of the University of Abuja, with the theme: “Enhancing Women and Youth Participation in Politics: Beyond Legality and Rhetoric.” Participants at the Webinar which was supported by Rosa Luxemburg Stiftung agreed that women and youth must wake up and use their numbers to canvas and galvanize support to challenge the status quo ante and elevate themselves from the hands of political gladiators who have been recycling themselves in offices since independence. In her presentation, Naomi A. Phinos (PhD) of the Department of Political Science and International Relations, University of Abuja said women and youths are more empowered in the developed world than males in the developing world. She therefore recommended that there should be electoral reforms which will accommodate and give equal opportunities to all participants and punish electoral offenders and that the political parties should advance plans to include women and youths as candidates and also in leadership. In her presentation, Dr. Linda Kwon-Ndung of the Department of Political Science, Federal University of Lafia said the shrinking performance of the Nigerian women and youths in active political participation can change if the needful is done. 